        "\n",
        "## 23.16 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Using random train-test splits for overlapping windows.** Adjacent windows share most observations, so random splits can create severe leakage.\n",
        "2. **Fitting PCA or scalers on the full dataset before splitting.** This uses test information in the representation.\n",
        "3. **Judging an embedding only by a pretty two-dimensional plot.** Visualization is useful, but downstream validation is necessary.\n",
        "4. **Confusing reconstruction with prediction.** Low reconstruction error does not imply good forecast performance.\n",
        "5. **Using invalid augmentations.** An augmentation must preserve task-relevant structure.\n",
        "6. **Ignoring baselines.** Handcrafted features and PCA are essential comparisons.\n",
        "7. **Overcompressing.** If $d$ is too small, important temporal information may be destroyed.\n",
        "8. **Undercompressing.** If $d$ is too large, the representation may memorize noise.\n",
        "9. **Failing to inspect nearest neighbors.** If nearest neighbors look unrelated in the original time domain, the embedding geometry may be poor.\n",
